# Product marketing context (template — fill in for your project)

This file is auto-loaded by the `coreyhaines31/marketing-skills` plugin (41 marketing sub-skills bundled via `bootstrap.sh`). When any of these skills fires (cold-email, copywriting, email-sequence, pricing-strategy, customer-research, ad-creative, social-content, etc.), it reads this file FIRST so it can skip foundational ICP/positioning questions.

To activate: copy this file to `.agents/product-marketing-context.md` (drop the `.example` suffix) at the root of any repo where you want the marketing skills to know your product context. Fill in each section.

If you don't fill this in, the marketing skills still work — they just ask the foundational questions every time.

## 1. Product overview

- **One-line description:** [What it is in a sentence.]
- **What it does (2-3 sentences):** [Core function + the customer transformation it produces.]
- **Product category:** [The shelf you sit on. How customers search for you.]
- **Product type:** [SaaS / marketplace / e-commerce / service / consulting / open-source / hybrid.]
- **Business model:** [Self-serve / sales-led / hybrid / community-led.]
- **Pricing shape:** [Free + paid tiers / consulting day rate / fixed-price project / per-seat / per-event.]

## 2. Target audience

- **Target company type:** [Industry / size / stage. Be specific.]
- **Target decision-makers:** [Roles + departments. Who signs the contract, who uses it daily.]
- **Primary use case:** [The main problem you solve.]
- **Jobs to be done (2-3):** [What customers "hire" you for, in their words.]
- **Specific scenarios:** [Concrete moments where they reach for you.]

## 3. Personas (B2B only)

For each stakeholder in the buying decision:

- **User:** [Daily user. What they care about. Friction they feel.]
- **Champion:** [Internal advocate. Why they push for you.]
- **Decision maker:** [Final approver. The objection they raise.]
- **Financial buyer:** [The one staring at price.]
- **Technical influencer:** [Security/IT/architecture review.]

## 4. Problems and pain points

- **Core challenge before you:** [In their words, not yours.]
- **Why current solutions fall short:** [Generic competitors / spreadsheets / agencies / DIY.]
- **What it costs them:** [Time + money + opportunity.]
- **Emotional tension:** [Stress, fear, doubt, FOMO. Real ones, not invented.]

## 5. Differentiation

- **3-5 reasons you're different:** [Not "we're the best" — specific structural differences.]
- **Proof points:** [Numbers, case studies, named customers, testimonial verbatim.]
- **What you do NOT do:** [Boundaries. The kind of customer you don't serve well.]

## 6. Customer language (verbatim)

The most valuable section. Drop in real phrases from:

- Customer support tickets
- Sales call transcripts
- Reviews (G2, Capterra, ProductHunt, Reddit)
- Internal Slack/Discord/forum threads
- Cold-email replies (positive AND negative)

Push for **exact phrases** over polished descriptions. "It's a pain to set up Zapier flows manually" beats "users want easier automation." Copy that resonates uses the words they already think in.

## 7. Competitors and alternatives

- **Direct competitors:** [Same shelf.]
- **Indirect alternatives:** [Different shelf, same job.]
- **Status quo / DIY:** [Doing nothing. Spreadsheets. The intern.]
- **For each:** [What they do well. Where they fail. How you compare.]

## 8. Channels and traffic

- **Primary acquisition:** [SEO / paid / partnerships / community / outbound / referrals.]
- **Where customers research:** [G2 / Reddit / Twitter / LinkedIn / industry blogs.]
- **What pre-arrival context typical visitors have:** [Cold / warm / familiar / brand-aware.]

## 9. Tone and voice

- **Voice:** [Direct / warm / technical / playful / authoritative.]
- **Words to avoid:** [Jargon you don't use. Industry clichés you reject.]
- **Words you reach for:** [Distinctive vocabulary that's "yours."]
- **Em dash policy / exclamation policy / first-person policy:** [Codify the small rules so every skill respects them.]

## 10. Foundational documents

Link to canonical sources:

- [Origin story / founding narrative]
- [Product roadmap]
- [Pricing page]
- [Brand guide / style guide]
- [Customer case studies]
- [Internal positioning memo]

---

## How to use this file with the marketing skills

After filling in: trigger any marketing skill (e.g. ask Claude "write me a cold email to <persona>" or "draft a launch announcement"). The skill auto-reads this file before asking you for setup info, so you go straight to the tactical work.

If you update positioning, re-run `/product-marketing-context` and the skill will diff + update the relevant sections.

## Voice firewall reminder

If your project uses the `humanizer` skill (also bundled in this substrate), every external-prose surface (cold-email, copywriting, social-content, ad-creative, sales-enablement, copy-editing, popup-cro output, email-sequence body, churn-prevention save offers) MUST be passed through `/humanizer` before publish. The marketing skills produce structure; humanizer locks voice. This is enforced at the substrate level and downstream of any context here.
